  "What is the tragedy of the commons?": "",
  "A theory that shared resources are always unlimited": "",
  "The degradation of shared resources when individuals act in self-interest because each person's benefit outweighs their share of the cost": "",
  "A principle that cooperation always prevents resource depletion": "",
  "A situation where resources are privately owned and well-managed": "",
  "The tragedy of the commons, described by Garrett Hardin in 1968, explains how shared resources like fisheries, atmosphere, and groundwater become overexploited when individuals maximize personal gain without bearing the full environmental cost.": "",
  "What is a keystone species?": "",
  "Any predator at the top of the food chain": "",
  "A species that only affects one other species in its habitat": "",
  "A species that has a disproportionately large impact on ecosystem structure and function relative to its abundance": "",
  "The most numerically abundant species in an ecosystem": "",
  "A keystone species exerts an outsized influence on its community relative to its population size, and its removal would cause dramatic changes to ecosystem structure, such as sea otters controlling sea urchin populations.": "",
  "What is the difference between r-selected and K-selected species?": "",
  "They differ only in physical body size, particularly regarding difference under normal circumstances": "",
  "They differ only in habitat preference, particularly regarding species in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "R-selected species produce many offspring with little parental care, while K-selected species produce few offspring with extensive parental care": "",
  "There is no meaningful difference between them in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "R-selected species (like insects and bacteria) reproduce rapidly with many offspring and short lifespans, while K-selected species (like elephants and whales) invest heavily in fewer offspring with longer lifespans and slower maturation.": "",
  "What is an ecological footprint?": "",
